metadata.name: Entrecroisement #161
metadata.description:
"Entrecroisement" is a French word meaning "intersections".
In this project, colored lines travel like rays of light that are reflected 
on the inner walls of a shape of a form in which it cannot exit. The different 
shapes are born (or filled) from these intersections.

The rendering time can take up to a minute
some parameters are adjustable with fx(params) and others are fixed according to the seeds 

To save a png file at 1500x2000 px type [s]

To render at 3000x4000 px resolution type [1] then press [s] 
type [2] to render at 4500x6000 px (can be long !)
---
100% done with p5js
some palettes comes from Werner's Nomenclature of Colors
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.
---

metadata.name: Winter Solstice #19
metadata.description:
I watched as the sun began to rise, its rays spreading out across the sky, illuminating the landscape. I felt a sense of peace and contentment, and for a moment, all of my worries and troubles melted away. I was truly happy, and felt grateful to be alive and able to witness this beautiful moment.

As the sun climbed higher in the sky, I continued to watch, taking in the beauty of the winter solstice. I knew that this moment was fleeting, and that soon the days would start to get longer and the cold winter weather would give way to spring. But for now, I was content to just stand there and enjoy the moment.

The winter solstice was a reminder to me that there was always beauty and wonder to be found in the world, even in the darkest of times, as I stood there, watching the sun rise.

metadata.name: Calligraphy #10
metadata.description:
Calligraphy is about formulating letters, not language. 

One of my first exercises as a design student (c. 1967) was learning to letter. Using a nib holding pen and India ink we sat for 5 weeks in class like monks constructing letters in the style of a font called 15th Century Chancery Italic Script. Our final grade was based on how well we hand lettered a paragraph. It was a grueling process that's why I remember it; quite the way to develop an appreciation for the letterforms and type faces. 

This algorithmic artwork is modern cuneiform. It is based on a theory I've developed called "Language of Vision" which in itself is an approach for creating a "plastic" image. The space-frame or background square consists of a subtle paper texture and defines the tablet. A resizable tile (spatial force) forms the boundary for a "stroke." The stroke within the tile element is created by joining two bezier curves. 

An algorithm called "fractions of the whole" is a "form of spatial organization" which divides the picture frame into randomly sized intervals along each axes that form the variable sized tile areas. The stroke is programmed to fit each area. This theory lends itself very nicely to algorithmic art and provides a general framework for generative art.

There is meaning in every image but that meaning comes from your experience and imagination.

Check out Dr. Bill Generative Art OG website @ drbillkolomyjec.com

metadata.name: Scapes #19
metadata.description:
Scapes is a long-form generative piece exploring an algorithm of a constrained range of limited color palettes and shapes. 

The initial inspiration was a closeup photo that I took of a parking lot's black pavement with red and white stripes. The photo was taken during the winter when the lot was covered with ice and melting water creating an image of minimal geometry mixed with analog grain and texture. 

As my exploration of the algorithm advanced, the inspiration grew to include styling influences of El Lissitzky's Prouns series. Similar to Prouns, the abstract shapes generated in Scapes conjure aerial views and urban architecture. Furthermore, El Lissitzky's Beat the Whites with the Red Wedge inspired a palette constrained to black, red, and white. The Constructive art of Beat the Whites with the Red Wedge additionally inspired the forms in Scapes to be primarily composed of geometric shapes.  

Scapes is a small collection reflecting the constrained nature of this piece. The scale might be small, but the output contains a lot of density that I enjoyed working into a limited palette. Enjoy!

Press the S key to download a 1,800 x 1,800 pixel PNG.

Created By: lukaszgraphz
Twitter: https://twitter.com/lukasz_x2

Art: August 2023
Created with p5js

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #793
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash ‚Äî they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash
